1. Introduction ¶

This project demonstrates how to perform instance segmentation using PyTorch’s torchvision library. Instance segmentation not only detects objects in an image but also generates a pixel-wise mask for each individual object. By leveraging a pre-trained Mask R-CNN, this project provides a hands-on example of how to load the model, apply it to images, and visualize the segmented instances with their respective masks, bounding boxes, and class labels.

The goal is to help you understand and implement a complete instance segmentation pipeline—from preprocessing to model inference and result visualization.

# visualize
def plot_image(img_tensor, title=None):
    """
    Plots an image from a tensor (C, H, W) or (H, W, C).
    
    Args:
        img_tensor (Tensor or ndarray): The image to display.
        title (str, optional): Title for the plot.
    """
    if isinstance(img_tensor, torch.Tensor):
        img_tensor = img_tensor.detach().cpu()
        if img_tensor.ndim == 3 and img_tensor.shape[0] in [1, 3]:
            img_tensor = img_tensor.permute(1, 2, 0)  # (C, H, W) -> (H, W, C)
        img = img_tensor.numpy()
    else:
        img = img_tensor

    # If image is normalized [0, 1] or [0, 255], adjust if needed
    if img.max() <= 1.0:
        img = img.clip(0, 1)
    else:
        img = img.astype(np.uint8)

    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 6))
    plt.imshow(img)
    if title:
        plt.title(title)
    plt.axis('off')
    plt.show()

plot_image(img_tensor, title="Input Image")

4. Model ¶

We will use Mask R-CNN

Mask R-CNN is a deep learning model designed for instance segmentation, a task that combines object detection and semantic segmentation. Unlike standard object detectors that output only bounding boxes and class labels, Mask R-CNN also predicts a binary mask for each detected object, allowing it to distinguish individual object instances at the pixel level.

Developed by Facebook AI Research (FAIR), Mask R-CNN extends the popular Faster R-CNN architecture by adding a parallel branch for mask prediction:

  • Backbone (e.g., ResNet + FPN): Extracts features from the input image.

  • Region Proposal Network (RPN): Proposes candidate object regions (bounding boxes).

  • Region of Interest (ROI) Align: Precisely crops features for each region (improving over ROI Pooling).

Heads:

  • Classification head: Predicts the class of each object.

  • Bounding box regressor: Refines the coordinates.

  • Mask head: Predicts a binary segmentation mask for each instance.

Mask R-CNN is widely used in applications requiring fine-grained object localization, such as:

  • Medical imaging.
  • Autonomous driving.
  • Photo editing.

In PyTorch, you can use a pre-trained version easily via:

model = torchvision.models.detection.maskrcnn_resnet50_fpn(pretrained=True)

This model is trained on the COCO dataset and can segment 80 common object categories right out of the box.

In [32]:
# Move to CPU and run inference
with torch.no_grad():
    prediction = model([img_tensor])[0]

The output predictions is a list of dictionaries (one dict per image). Each dictionary contains:

  • boxes

Tensor of shape [N, 4]

Each row is the bounding box coordinates [x_min, y_min, x_max, y_max] for one detected object.

  • labels

Tensor of shape [N]

The predicted class labels for each detected object (integers corresponding to COCO class indices).

  • scores

Tensor of shape [N]

The confidence scores (probabilities) for each detected object. Values between 0 and 1.

  • masks

Tensor of shape [N, 1, H, W]

Binary masks for each detected object. Usually the mask pixels are probabilities between 0 and 1, which you can threshold (e.g., > 0.5) to get a binary mask.

N is the number of objects detected.

# Set a confidence threshold to filter low-confidence detections (e.g., 0.7)
threshold = 0.7

print("Detected objects with confidence scores:")
for score, label in zip(scores, labels):
    if score >= threshold:
        print(f"{COCO_INSTANCE_CATEGORY_NAMES[label]}: {score:.3f}")

# Convert original image to OpenCV format

threshold = 0.5

for i in range(len(masks)):
    if scores[i] >= threshold:
        mask = masks[i, 0].mul(255).byte().cpu().numpy()
        label = COCO_INSTANCE_CATEGORY_NAMES[labels[i]]
        score = scores[i].item()
        box = boxes[i].cpu().numpy().astype(int)
        
        # Generate a random color
        color = np.random.randint(0, 255, (3,), dtype=np.uint8).tolist()

        # Create colored background
        colored_mask = np.zeros_like(img_cv, dtype=np.uint8)
        for c in range(3):
            colored_mask[:, :, c] = color[c]
        mask_area = mask > 128
        img_cv[mask_area] = cv2.addWeighted(img_cv, 0.5, colored_mask, 0.5, 0)[mask_area]

        # Find contours and draw them
        contours, _ = cv2.findContours(mask, cv2.RETR_EXTERNAL, cv2.CHAIN_APPROX_SIMPLE)
        cv2.drawContours(img_cv, contours, -1, color, 2)

        # Add label
        x1, y1 = box[0], box[1]
        text = f"{label}: {score:.2f}"
        cv2.putText(img_cv, text, (x1, y1 - 10), cv2.FONT_HERSHEY_SIMPLEX, 0.6, color, 2)
